# Backend Environment Variables

Copy these to your backend hosting service (Railway, Render, Heroku, etc.):

## Production Variables

```env
# Database Configuration
DATABASE_URL=postgresql+psycopg://user:password@host:port/database_name

# JWT Security
JWT_SECRET_KEY=your-secret-key-here
ACCESS_TOKEN_EXPIRE_MINUTES=30

# CORS Configuration
BACKEND_CORS_ORIGINS=https://your-vercel-frontend-url.vercel.app

# Optional: Debug Mode (set to false in production)
DEBUG=false
```

## How to Generate JWT_SECRET_KEY

### On Windows PowerShell:
```powershell
$bytes = [System.Security.Cryptography.RandomNumberGenerator]::GetBytes(32)
[System.BitConverter]::ToString($bytes).Replace("-", "").ToLower()
```

### On Mac/Linux:
```bash
openssl rand -hex 32
```

## Example for Railway

When deploying to Railway:
1. In the Railway dashboard, go to your project
2. Click "Variables"
3. Add each environment variable from above
4. Replace example values with your actual values:
   - `user:password@host:port` - Railway provides this after you add PostgreSQL plugin
   - `your-secret-key-here` - Generate a random key using commands above
   - `your-vercel-frontend-url` - Get this from your Vercel deployment URL

## Example for Render

Same process as Railway:
1. In Render dashboard, go to your Web Service
2. Click "Environment"
3. Add variables in the format: `KEY=VALUE`

## Example PostgreSQL Connection Strings

### Railway (provided automatically):
```
postgresql+psycopg://user:password@aws-1-us-east-1.railway.internal:5432/railway
```

### Supabase:
```
postgresql+psycopg://postgres:password@db.project-id.supabase.co:5432/postgres
```

### Local Development:
```
postgresql+psycopg://postgres:password@localhost:5432/attendance_db
```

## Testing Backend Deployment

After setting environment variables:

1. Check backend health:
   ```
   curl https://your-backend-url/api/health
   ```
   Response should be: `{"status":"ok"}`

2. Test login endpoint:
   ```
   curl -X POST https://your-backend-url/api/auth/login \
     -H "Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded" \
     -d "username=admin@company.com&password=password123"
   ```
